It doesn&#x27;t work, the &str could come from completely different types in the two branches.<p>I.e. one branch could be created by .as_slice() on a String, the other could be created by referencing a global, e.g.<p><pre><code>  let s = if cond {
      let some_string = create_it();
      some_string.as_slice()
  } else {
      &quot;literals are always-valid &str&#x27;s&quot;
  };
</code></pre>
`some_string`s destructor should only be run if the first branch was taken.
